Adjust rack to middle position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry
produce (except @Riced Cauliflower{12%ounce}).

Halve @Poblano Pepper{2} lengthwise; remove ribs and seeds. Place poblanos on a
#baking sheet{}, cut sides down. Drizzle each half with @Cooking Oil{6%teaspoon};
rub to coat. Season with @Salt{} and @Pepper{}.

Roast on middle rack until softened, ~{15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, zest and quarter @Lime{1} (for 4 servings, zest one lime and quarter
both). Halve, peel, and dice @Yellow Onion{1}. Dice @Roma Tomato{1}. Mince
@Chili Pepper{1}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @Sour Cream{4%tablespoon} and lime zest to taste. Add
@water{} 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency. Season
with @Salt{} and @Pepper{}.

Heat a large drizzle of oil in a large, preferably ovenproof, pan over
medium-high heat. Add onion and cook, stirring occasionally, until slightly
softened, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add cauliflower rice and cook, stirring occasionally, until browned,
~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir in @Veggie Stock Concentrate{1}, @Southwest Spice Blend{1%tablespoon},
half the tomato, @water{1/4%cup}, @Salt{3/4%tsp}, and pepper. (For 4 servings,
use 1/3 cup water and 1 1/2 tsp salt.) Cook, stirring, until softened,
~{2-3%minutes}.

Turn off heat; stir in @Butter{1%tablespoon} (2 TBSP for 4) until melted.

Once poblanos are done roasting, carefully stuff each half with as much filling
as will fit. Nestle into pan with remaining filling. Sprinkle poblano halves
with @Monterey Jack Cheese{1/2%cup}.

> TIP: If your pan isn't ovenproof, transfer filling and stuffed poblanos now to
> a small baking dish.

Bake on middle rack until cheese melts, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Meanwhile, in a #medium bowl{}, combine @Guacamole{4%tablespoon}, remaining
tomato, and lime juice to taste. Season with @Salt{} and @Pepper{}.

Divide remaining filling and stuffed poblanos between plates. Top with
guacamole, crema, and chili if desired. Serve with any remaining lime wedges on
the side.